HEADWORD: Manichee
<hw>Man"i*chee</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>Manichaeus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>manich⟦eacute⟧en</ets>.]</ety> <def>A
believer in the doctrines of <persfn>Manes</persfn>, a Persian of the
third century A. D., who taught a dualism in which Light is regarded as
the source of Good, and Darkness as the source of Evil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>Manichaeans</qex> stand as representatives of dualism
pushed to its utmost development.</q> <rj><qau>Tylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manichean</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Manichaean</ent>⟦br⟧
